1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,880
A function Python is like a mini program inside your program.

2

00:00:03,880  -->  00:00:06,600
You define a function using the def keyword

3

00:00:06,600  -->  00:00:10,080
followed by the function name and parentheses.

4

00:00:10,080  -->  00:00:13,780
Think of defining a function like writing down a recipe in your restaurant.

5

00:00:13,780  -->  00:00:16,300
You list out the ingredients, inputs,

6

00:00:16,300  -->  00:00:19,940
and steps, making it easy to follow and repeat.

7

00:00:19,940  -->  00:00:22,260
When you're ready to use this recipe,

8

00:00:22,260  -->  00:00:25,940
you simply use Python to invoke or call the function,

9

00:00:25,940  -->  00:00:28,100
just like you would when cooking a meal,

10

00:00:28,100  -->  00:00:30,965
following those steps to your recipe.

11

00:00:30,965  -->  00:00:34,910
Earlier in the course, we learned about various methods that Python comes

12

00:00:34,910  -->  00:00:39,790
prepared with or pre-baked with that are called built-in functions.

13

00:00:39,790  -->  00:00:42,650
Python is very powerful because right out of the box,

14

00:00:42,650  -->  00:00:46,090
it can do many incredible processes that we've looked at,

15

00:00:46,090  -->  00:00:49,750
such as print, outputs text to the console.

16

00:00:49,750  -->  00:00:54,370
Len returns the length of an object like a string or a list.

17

00:00:54,370  -->  00:00:57,985
Sum adds all items in an iterable together,

18

00:00:57,985  -->  00:01:02,280
such as a list and type returns the data type of an object.

19

00:01:02,280  -->  00:01:03,800
These functions are part of

20

00:01:03,800  -->  00:01:07,720
Python's standard library and don't require you to define them yourself.

21

00:01:07,720  -->  00:01:11,560
They're highly optimized and designed to handle a variety of

22

00:01:11,560  -->  00:01:16,955
common tasks that you will use regularly in your day-to-day Python programming.

23

00:01:16,955  -->  00:01:19,480
User-defined functions, on the other hand,

24

00:01:19,480  -->  00:01:21,900
are those that you create to preform

25

00:01:21,900  -->  00:01:26,385
specific tasks that are not covered by Python's built-in functions.

26

00:01:26,385  -->  00:01:28,130
These are functions you,

27

00:01:28,130  -->  00:01:32,150
as the programmer, create to perform specific tasks.

28

00:01:32,150  -->  00:01:35,850
They allow you to define steps tailored to your specific needs,

29

00:01:35,850  -->  00:01:40,370
so you aren't limited to the built-in functions Python provides alone.

30

00:01:40,370  -->  00:01:44,670
This way, you can reuse your own code whenever needed,

31

00:01:44,670  -->  00:01:47,990
saving time and keeping things organized.

32

00:01:47,990  -->  00:01:52,050
You define these functions using the def keyword like this.

33

00:01:52,050  -->  00:01:54,010
In this user-defined function,

34

00:01:54,010  -->  00:01:57,100
we write our own custom function called say_hi.

35

00:01:57,100  -->  00:01:58,530
That will do exactly that.

36

00:01:58,530  -->  00:02:00,160
Print the phrase we define.

37

00:02:00,160  -->  00:02:02,730
"Hi there", with a return statement.

38

00:02:02,730  -->  00:02:08,155
Defining a function like this allows us to reuse the code anytime we need a greeting,

39

00:02:08,155  -->  00:02:11,890
without having to retype the print statement over and over again.

40

00:02:11,890  -->  00:02:13,630
We can just do this,

41

00:02:13,630  -->  00:02:19,725
and it will remember the print statement and any logic we add to our functions.

42

00:02:19,725  -->  00:02:22,390
User-defined functions work really well for

43

00:02:22,390  -->  00:02:26,390
executing a block of code all at once after being called.

44

00:02:26,390  -->  00:02:31,810
But what if we need to handle a large amount of data or sequences one step at a time?

45

00:02:31,810  -->  00:02:35,470
You might think that we could write a normal function,

46

00:02:35,470  -->  00:02:38,350
but there is another more efficient way to

47

00:02:38,350  -->  00:02:42,250
handle big datasets and sequences called generators.

48

00:02:42,250  -->  00:02:45,630
Generators are a special type of function in Python,

49

00:02:45,630  -->  00:02:47,890
similarly to regular functions,

50

00:02:47,890  -->  00:02:50,890
but using the yield keyword instead of return.

51

00:02:50,890  -->  00:02:55,010
They produce items one at a time and only when asked,

52

00:02:55,010  -->  00:02:59,070
making the memory efficient for handling large amounts of data.

53

00:02:59,070  -->  00:03:02,245
Imagine that your restaurant, you're baking cookies.

54

00:03:02,245  -->  00:03:03,860
Over the course of the day,

55

00:03:03,860  -->  00:03:07,430
you might bake hundreds or even thousands of cookies.

56

00:03:07,430  -->  00:03:10,160
If you bake 1,000 cookies at once,

57

00:03:10,160  -->  00:03:15,280
you might have cookies getting cold or still if they're left out all day long.

58

00:03:15,280  -->  00:03:18,280
You don't need to bake all of the cookies at once.

59

00:03:18,280  -->  00:03:21,220
Instead, you can produce a batch of cookies,

60

00:03:21,220  -->  00:03:25,180
serve them, then bake the next batch when it's needed, and so on.

61

00:03:25,180  -->  00:03:30,870
Generator functions operate in a very similar way to this cooking baking example.

62

00:03:30,870  -->  00:03:34,160
They yield one item at a time,

63

00:03:34,160  -->  00:03:36,740
pausing until the next item is requested.

64

00:03:36,740  -->  00:03:39,200
This makes them incredibly useful when dealing with

65

00:03:39,200  -->  00:03:43,500
large sequences of data or when you don't need everything at once.

66

00:03:43,500  -->  00:03:46,220
They can be difficult to grasp at first.

67

00:03:46,220  -->  00:03:50,240
But do not worry once you see an example in action,

68

00:03:50,240  -->  00:03:53,190
it will make a whole lot more sense.

69

00:03:53,190  -->  00:03:55,590
Let's take a look at functions,

70

00:03:55,590  -->  00:03:59,490
and we'll look at a simple example of generators for context.

71

00:03:59,490  -->  00:04:02,130
We can define a function with a few elements.

72

00:04:02,130  -->  00:04:04,640
We'll start with a def keyword,

73

00:04:04,640  -->  00:04:08,170
def, a function name, which in this case,

74

00:04:08,170  -->  00:04:11,450
is count_up_to, and we can pass in

75

00:04:11,450  -->  00:04:15,885
arguments such as Max to set an upper limit to count_up_to.

76

00:04:15,885  -->  00:04:22,370
We can then use the yield keyword instead of return to produce values one at a time,

77

00:04:22,370  -->  00:04:25,750
pausing the function while keeping its state or

78

00:04:25,750  -->  00:04:31,250
memory of where it lasts was in the generation process after each yield.

79

00:04:38,900  -->  00:04:43,750
Often generators will include a loop like while or

80

00:04:43,750  -->  00:04:47,780
for to repeatedly yield values until a condition is met,

81

00:04:47,780  -->  00:04:49,820
like reaching our upper limit.

82

00:04:49,820  -->  00:04:59,290
We'll then create a generator object like this counter equals count_up_to 3.

83

00:04:59,960  -->  00:05:02,960
Which doesn't run the function right away,

84

00:05:02,960  -->  00:05:05,500
but returns a special generator object that

85

00:05:05,500  -->  00:05:08,760
we can iterate over to get values one at a time.

86

00:05:08,760  -->  00:05:11,860
To use our generator, we'll use next,

87

00:05:11,860  -->  00:05:18,220
which retrieves the next value each time next is called on the generator object,

88

00:05:18,220  -->  00:05:22,120
continuing until the generator is exhausted.

89

00:05:22,120  -->  00:05:24,260
We'll execute the cell block,

90

00:05:24,260  -->  00:05:27,760
and then each run will print outputs like this.

91

00:05:27,760  -->  00:05:31,975
Once we run print next counter,

92

00:05:31,975  -->  00:05:34,990
we then get one.

93

00:05:35,300  -->  00:05:38,930
We'll run this again, and we'll get two.

94

00:05:38,930  -->  00:05:42,315
We'll run this one more time. We'll get three.

95

00:05:42,315  -->  00:05:44,100
We'll run this once more,

96

00:05:44,100  -->  00:05:47,780
and then we'll get a stop iteration error.

97

00:05:47,780  -->  00:05:49,520
Once the limit is reached,

98

00:05:49,520  -->  00:05:53,860
which is defined as three in our function here,

99

00:05:53,860  -->  00:05:59,600
our generator is told to go up to and include the max, which is three.

100

00:05:59,600  -->  00:06:02,335
Then we cannot run the generator, again.

101

00:06:02,335  -->  00:06:06,700
What makes a function a function in a generator generator?

102

00:06:06,700  -->  00:06:09,345
Let's dive into the differences of each.

103

00:06:09,345  -->  00:06:12,130
Then what makes them similar.
